top.value: DHS Transportation Security Administration - International Aviation Security Technical Training

ILEAs help advance U.S. interests through international cooperation while promoting global social, political and economic stability through combating crime. ILEAs provide high quality training and technical assistance, support institution building, enhance enforcement capabilities and foster positive relationships between American law enforcement agencies and their counterparts in each respective region.

These on-site advisors provide technical assistance in a variety of areas such as: targeting and risk management, selectivity, duty collection, appraisement, classification, cargo inspection, passenger inspection, high-tech equipment, general management, integrity programs, canine enforcement, smuggling, information collection and analysis, and legal/regulatory considerations.

To further the informational exchange with partner nations by reinforcing inspectional techniques and methodologies with counterpart law enforcement agencies in the host nations own operating environment. Skills previously presented in the US during IBIT by conducting practical exercise at critical port(s) of entry identified by host national. The goal of this program is to help build an internal train-the-trainer capacity and eventually infuse the curriculum into the formal training regimen of the host nation.
To provide an effective means of identifying high-risk shipments and provide the knowledge and skills necessary to improve cargo targeting capabilities

Border security assessments are intended to provide CBP-INA, U.S. State Department and our in-country advisors with information on the current stat of border and cargo security within the applicable foreign country.

To share CBP inspectional techniques and methodologies with foreign counterparts in their own international airport environment in an effort to further the global fight against proliferation and terrorism. To provide or enhance the skills and knowledge necessary to carry our effective inspection, detection of contraband, cargo and passenger processing at an international airport.

To share CBP inspectional techniques and methodologies with foreign counterparts in an effort to further the fight against proliferation and global terrorism. To provide the skills and knowledge necessary to carry out effective inspection and processing of cargo and passengers at an international airport.

The objection of this training is to provide an overview of seaport operations and current threats in the host nations seaport environment. Both classroom and field exercises reinforce the topics discussed.
